Introduction:¶

John Snow’s groundbreaking work in 1854 is often celebrated as one of the earliest applications of data visualization to address a public health crisis. Faced with a cholera outbreak in London, Snow mapped the locations of cholera cases, eventually tracing the source to a contaminated water pump on Broad Street. His work not only saved lives but also demonstrated the power of visual data analysis in uncovering the root causes of public health issues.

For this assignment, we were asked to redesign a significant historical information graphic using contemporary, interactive methods. I chose to reimagine Snow’s cholera map, drawing on both the historical significance of the outbreak and my familiarity with the subject matter. The dataset I used was sourced from the Google Drive folder shared by Dr. Gabby.

My primary goal was to create an interactive visualization of the cholera outbreak, highlighting the correlation between water pump locations and death counts. The redesign is intended to enhance user engagement and deepen data comprehension. Through interactive features like tooltips and filters, users can explore the outbreak data in a dynamic way, focusing on specific regions or time periods as they choose. This approach not only honors John Snow's original mission to use data visualization for public health awareness but also updates it to meet the expectations of modern audiences who value intuitive, interactive insights.

import pandas as pd
import folium
from folium.plugins import HeatMap, MarkerCluster

# The snow map
deaths_df = pd.DataFrame({
    "death_count": [1, 1, 1, 1, 1],
    "x_latitude": [51.513418, 51.513418, 51.513418, 51.513361, 51.513361],
    "y_longitude": [-0.137930, -0.137930, -0.137930, -0.137883, -0.137883]
})
pumps_df = pd.DataFrame({
    "pump_name": ["Broad St.", "Crown Chapel", "Gt Marlborough", "Dean St.", "So Soho"],
    "x_coordinate": [51.513341, 51.513876, 51.514906, 51.512354, 51.512139],
    "y_coordinate": [-0.136668, -0.139586, -0.139671, -0.131630, -0.133594]
})
In [6]:
# Initialize map centered on the outbreak location
m = folium.Map(location=[51.513, -0.137], zoom_start=16)

# Add death locations with heatmap
heat_data = list(zip(deaths_df['x_latitude'], deaths_df['y_longitude'], deaths_df['death_count']))
HeatMap(heat_data).add_to(m)

HeatMap(heat_data, radius=10, gradient={0.2: 'blue', 0.5: 'lime', 0.9: 'red'}).add_to(m)

In [7]:
# Adding Pump Markers with toggling
pump_layer = folium.FeatureGroup(name="Water Pumps", show=True)
for _, row in pumps_df.iterrows():
    folium.Marker(
        location=[row['x_coordinate'], row['y_coordinate']],
        popup=f"<b>Pump Name:</b> {row['pump_name']}",
        tooltip="Click for Pump Info",
        icon=folium.Icon(color='blue', icon='info-sign')
    ).add_to(pump_layer)
pump_layer.add_to(m)

# Adding Clustered Death Markers for Interactivity
marker_cluster = MarkerCluster(name="Cholera Cases").add_to(m)
for _, row in deaths_df.iterrows():
    folium.Marker(
        location=[row['x_latitude'], row['y_longitude']],
        popup=f"<b>Deaths:</b> {row['death_count']}",
        tooltip="Cholera Case"
    ).add_to(marker_cluster)

# Historical Context: Adding Text/HTML Information
historical_note = """
<b>Historical Context:</b> John Snow's 1854 cholera map showed a clear correlation between cholera cases and the contaminated Broad Street pump.
"""
folium.Marker(
    [51.513, -0.137],
    icon=folium.DivIcon(html=f'<div style="font-size: 12pt; color : black">{historical_note}</div>')
).add_to(m)
